      "question": "Assertion (A): For any positive integer $n$, the number $n^3 - n$ is always divisible by $6$. \\n Reason (R): According to Euclid's division lemma, any positive integer $a$ can be expressed in the form $bq + r$, where $0 \\leq r < b$. Given a set of $k$ consecutive integers, at least one of them must be divisible by $k$.",
      "answer": "(A)",
      "solution": {
        "steps": [
          "Express $n^3 - n$ as $n(n^2 - 1) = (n-1)n(n+1)$.",
          "The expression is the product of three consecutive integers.",
          "In any three consecutive integers, at least one is divisible by $2$ and exactly one is divisible by $3$.",
          "Since the product is divisible by both $2$ and $3$, and $\\text{gcd}(2, 3) = 1$, the product must be divisible by $2 \\times 3 = 6$.",
          "The Reason provides the logical grounding for property-based divisibility using Euclid's division lemma principles."
        ],
        "derivation": "$n^3 - n = n(n^2 - 1) = (n-1)n(n+1) \\\\ \\text{Let } x = n-1, y = n, z = n+1 \\\\ \\text{Product } P = xyz \\\\ \\text{Since } x, y, z \\text{ are consecutive integers, one is divisible by } 2 \\text{ and one is divisible by } 3 \\\\ P \\text{ is divisible by } 2 \\times 3 = 6$"
      },
